<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="5" align="CENTER">
<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">I'm on the fence on this subject.   On the one hand, there are some ridiculous aspects to the way smithing works.  On the other, if your only reason for pursuing a trade skill is financial gain, I'd say you were missing the point.  <p>

The game provides many different ways to pursue personal enjoyment.  For some it's purely the hack and slash, fingerwiggling variety.  For others, it's completing many different quests.  Still others may prefer the satisfaction of mastering a given skill (in this case, smithing.)  Most folks do some of each, but heavily weighted towards adventuring.  Looked at in that light, smithing is a good challenge.  It's not easy to become a master smith.<p>

That being said, it's absurd that for example, you can't find sharpening stones anywhere in eastern Antonica.  They should be available by the boatload at any vendor that sells edged weapons.  Otherwise, most swords/knives would be better suited for bludgeoning than for slicing.  And every smithy should have the raw materials for its craft, otherwise, they'd be empty storefronts.<p>

The new enhancements to smithing (plate mail, racially-specialized and magical armor/weapons,) should help things considerably, both for smiths and enchanters.  Time will tell.</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="CENTER">
